# real mode
- all intel processors have this
- 16 bit mode they start in when switched on, compatibility mode
- 1 mb of ram
- based on origional x86 design
 - 8086 processor
- no security at all
 - kernel/ OS can be destroyed
 - no hardware or software security
- memory is accessed through the segmntation memory model
- all code in real mode is required to be 16 bits
 - this can be changed to 32 bits on a per command basis

# user land/ kernel land
- kernel land is any code operating with the maximum poeeible priviledges
 - aka ring 0
 - user land is ring 3
  - must ask kernel to od things
